A thread is the smallest unit of execution within a program
Thread is a lightweight process that executes a part of a program.
Example:
Playing the music , while downloading the file


Multithreading:
Multithreading means executing multiple threads simultaneously within a single program.

Advantages:
Improves performance
Saves time (parallel execution)
Better CPU utilization
Smooth user experience (no freezing UI)

How we can achieve the mutithreading:
1) by using the thread class:
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running...");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();
        t1.start(); // starts thread
    }
}

2)by implementing the runnable interface

class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running...");
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyRunnable obj = new MyRunnable();
        Thread t1 = new Thread(obj);
        t1.start();
    }
}

States of the thread:

1. New
👉 Thread is created but not started

2. Runnable
👉 Thread is ready to run (waiting for CPU)

3. Running
👉 Thread is executing

4. Waiting / Blocked
👉 Thread is waiting for resource or another thread

5. Terminated (Dead)
👉 Execution completed

VIMP: Important Methods in Thread
start() → starts thread
run() → contains code
sleep() → pause thread
join() → wait for another thread
isAlive() → checks if thread is running


Real-Life Examples
✔️ 1. Web Browser
Multiple tabs → multiple threads
✔️ 2. Gaming
Sound, graphics, input → different threads
✔️ 3. Banking App
Balance check + transaction simultaneously
